{
  "text": "Our study has a number of limitations. We defined elimination as incidence below 1/1,000 person-years. However, real elimination is achieved when both incidence and prevalence reach 0%. Microsimulation allows for such an analysis, and we found that in a model population of about 35,000 people, by 2080, 99% of all model runs predict that HIV prevalence reaches 0% in model A ( Figure S5) . In model D this point is reached only in year 2116 for the UTT scenario, and in year 2164 for continued scale-up of ART at CD4 count #350 cells/ml ( Figure S5 ). In addition, we did not model the development and transmission of drug-resistant strains. Both acquired resistance (development of resistance within an individual on treatment) and transmitted resistance (spread of drug-resistant strains) will have an impact on the effectiveness of treatment programs, and will consequently result in a less profound effect of the current ART scale-up or UTT in South Africa. It is currently unclear, however, to what extent the fears of rapidly spreading drug resistance expressed at the start of the ART scale-up were justified [CITATION_1] . The prevalence of drug resistance remains low in South Africa after nearly 10 y of scaling up ART [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . In addition, adherence to treatment is as high as in many high-income countries [CITATION_4] , and survival of patients on treatment in sub-Saharan Africa approaches general life expectancy [CITATION_5] , suggesting that resistance may not become a major problem in South Africa in the near future.",
  "correct_citation": {
